edium. These essays develop innovative cultural strategies for reading, re-reading and re-using photographs, as well as for (re)creating photographs and other artworks and evoke varied sites of memory in contemporary landscapes: from sites of war and other violence through the lost places of indigenous peoples to the once-familiar everyday places of home, family, neighborhood and community. Paying close attention to the settings in which such photographs are made and used--family collections, public archives, museums, newspapers, art galleries--the contributors consider how meanings in photographs may be shifted, challenged and renewed over time and for different purposes--from historical inquiry to quests for personal, familial, ethnic and national identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aHistoryvSources. 0aHistoryxSourcesxSources. 0aPhotographyxPhilosophy. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspects. 0aSpace and time. 7aPhotography / General.2bisacsh1 aBriggs, Marlene A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmiko McAllister, Kirsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagopian, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirsch, Marianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaye, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuhn, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuhn, Annette, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLangford, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLowry, Glen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcAllister, Kirsten Emiko, 